Turkish Sutlac  INGREDIENTS

½ cup uncooked rice
2 cups water
4 and ½ cups milk, divided
1 cup sugar
2 and ½ tablespoons cornstarch
1 tsp vanilla extract 
INSTRUCTIONS

Cook the rice with water in a large saucepan over medium heat until tender (no need for rinsing the rice before cooking). Rice won’t absorb all the water, there will still be some in the pan. And it will look creamy.
Add in milk and sugar and bring it to boil. Then reduce the heat and let it simmer for about 10 minutes over low heat. 
In a small bowl, make a slurry by whisking together ½ cup milk and 2 tablespoons of corn starch until smooth. Pour it slowly into the simmering rice. Stir the rice constantly while doing this. Keep stirring and let the mixture simmer until it thickens, for 10-15 minutes.
mix in vanilla extract.
Bake the rice pudding. To do this, remove the pan from heat and pour the hot mixture into individual oven-proof cups like ramekins or clay cups. Place them into an oven tray. Fill half of the oven tray with water so that the pudding has that nice silky skin layer on the top. This will also keep the rice pudding creamy and prevent it from getting dry. 
Carefully place the tray on the top shelf of a preheated oven (at 400F/200C). Bake them uncovered until golden brown. It is even better if you have some burnt bits. Watch their top and remove from the oven when they reach the desired golden color.
Remove from the heat and carefully take the bowls from the tray. Let them completely cool down and chill in the refrigerator for a few hours before serving.
Optionally, you can top them with nuts like hazelnuts or pistachios.
#sütlaç #turkishfood #ricepudding #murselandanna #90dayfiance #turkiye #antalya #tatlı

This is one of my favorite Turkish dishes. It’s fresh and light. I Love it!  Kisir
3 cups bulgar 
3.5 cups boiling water
1/4 cup olive oil
2 medium onions finely diced
5 tablespoons of tomato paste
4 small cucumbers diced 
1 bunch parsley chopped. 
2 lemons or 1/3 cup lemon juice
Salt and pepper to taste
Start with hydrating the bulgar add boiling water to dry bulgar let sit until all bulgar has soaked up all the water. 
I’m a pan add olive oil, then add finely diced onions sauté until onion is very soft. Do not let caramelize. Then add tomato paste and cook until oil and onions are fully combined with tomato paste. 
Add this mixture to the bulgar and mix thoroughly. Add chopped parsley and cucumbers. 
Add lemon juice to your taste. 
Salt and pepper to your taste. I like a lot of lemon juice. 
Serve with lettuce and pickles. #kisir #turkiye #turkishfood #murselandanna #90dayfiance

First time making kunefe over 2 weeks ago.  Kunefe
2 cups sugar
1 cup water
Squeeze of lemon juice
1 pound shredded phyllo dough
1 cup melted butter
1.5 pounds mozzarella cheese
3/4 cup ricotta cheese
 First make a syrup with sugar, water, and lemon juice. Bring to boil and make sure sugar is dissolved. Turn off heat. 
Cut shredded phyllo dough into small pieces. 
Mix with 1 cup melted butter.
Press 1/2 phyllo and butter mixture into a 10 or 12 inch pan. 
Combine ricotta and mozzarella add this to the top of phyllo dough. Then finish with second layer of phyllo dough mixture. Press down. Bake at 350 for 30 minutes or until phyllo is golden brown. 
Remove from oven, pour syrup over cooked kunefe. Serve.

Did you know all natural honey crystalizes? That’s one way you’ll know you have REAL honey! We get asked this all of the time…why is my honey hard? Why does my honey look like sugar? Honey crystalizes due to the glucose in the honey. We lightly filter our honey which leaves pollen in the honey…the pollen creates a structure for the honey to crystallize on. It’s all natural so nothing to worry about. #rawhoney #honey #beekeeping #beekeepers

I’ve made this recipe twice now! It’s so easy and makes a beautiful loaf! No more buying bread at the store!  Mursel eats a loaf of French bread a day…so this is for him and the family. Rustic no knead bread
3 cups bread flour
2 tsp salt
2 tsp yeast
1.5 cups warm water
Mix until combined, the dough will be very soft and sticky! Let rise for 2.5-3hours. 
Preheat oven to 450. Place Dutch oven inside oven with lid. Heat 30 minutes. 
While oven is heating place dough on floured counter, fold dough over onto itself to form a loose ball. Place dough ball on parchment paper. 
Once oven and Dutch oven are heated place parchment paper with dough into Dutch oven and cover with lid. 
Bake 30 minutes. 
Remove lid and bake 12 minutes more. 
Remove from oven to cool.

Here is my monthly update on my gastric sleeve surgery I had April 15th! Im@down 65 pounds! This month has been slower, but that’s ok. It’s not going to be rapid all the time! I’m down 10 pounds this month. Looking back on this photo of the day I had surgery gives me so many feelings! I can’t believe I let myself get to this point. I knew I had to do something. My body ached, I hurt every time I stood or had to stand working for hours. Before Gokhan could walk or crawl I’d think to myself how can I keep up with my little guy! I couldn’t. Now I have more energy and I can finally wear clothes I bought 4 years ago. I’m so happy I made the decision to have surgery. It hasn’t been easy, it’s been difficult and mentally tough. I know this has been the best decision for me, my family and for my relationship with my husband. I want to thank everyone following my journey. I made Ceviche de Soya tonight. I haven’t made this in years! A 3/4 cup has about 17 grams of protein.

8 ounces texturized soy protein
1 English cucumber diced
5 Roma tomatoes diced
1 small onion diced
1 diced jalapeño
1 bunch cilantro chopped 
3/4-1cup fresh lime juice
Salt to taste
Tostadas 
Avocado
Rehydrate soy protein by adding it to water that has been heated to boiling then shut off. Let soy sit until soft and plump. Rinse in cold water then squeeze out as much water from the soy as you can. Place in a large bowl. Add cucumber, tomatoes, onion, and cilantro mix well. Then add lime juice and salt to your liking. I like a lot of lime juice. This is where alot if flavor comes from. Serve over a tostada. Or you can eat as is. You can serve with avocado and Valentina’s hot sauce. #vegan #soya #ceviche #cevichedesoya

I made this curry lentil stew tonight. Sorry I don’t have a better photo. It was very good! Everyone loved it. I did add coconut milk at the end. This recipe was doubled. I wanted left overs for lunches. * 2 tablespoons olive oil
* 1 large onion chopped
* 2 carrots cut into discs
* 3 cloves garlic grated
* 1 teaspoon ginger grated
* 2 teaspoons curry powder
* 1 teaspoon turmeric powder
* 1 teaspoon ground cumin
* ¼ teaspoon red pepper flakes more or less to taste
* 5 cups vegetable broth or more if needed
* 1 can (15 ounces) crushed tomatoes
* 1 cup dry lentils green or brown
* 1 pound potatoes peeled and cut into bite-size chunks
* 5 ounces kale or spinach, chopped
* 1 teaspoons salt or more to taste
* 2 twists black pepper
* 1 lime optional, to squeeze on top

Instructions 

* Heat 2 tablespoons olive oil in a large pot or Dutch oven. Add 1 large onion (chopped) and 2 carrots cut into thin slices and fry them gently for 3 minutes.  Add 3 cloves garlic (grated), 1 teaspoon ginger (grated), 2 teaspoons curry powder, 1 teaspoon turmeric powder, 1 teaspoon ground cumin, and ¼ teaspoon red pepper flakes and fry for one more minute, stirring often.
* 
Add 5 cups vegetable broth, 1 can (15 ounces) crushed tomatoes, 1 cup dry lentils (rinsed), 1 pound potatoes (peeled and diced), 5 ounces kale (chopped), and season with 1 teaspoons salt and 2 twists black pepper.

Cover with a lid, bring to a boil on high heat, then crack the top open and let it simmer on medium heat for about 30 minutes or until the lentils are cooked. Stir occasionally.

Taste and adjust for salt and spices, then serve the soup in a bowl with a squeeze of lime or lemon on top and optionally some fresh cilantro or parsley. @theplantbasedschool #meatless #meatlessmeals
